05102nam a22007935i 9781501755415DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20212017nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97815017554157 a10.1515/97815017554152doi  a(DE-B1597)567949  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aPG3488.O4bZ6225 2017 7aHIS0320002bisacsh04a891.73/442231 aCongdon, Lee, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSolzhenitsyn :bThe Historical-Spiritual Destinies of Russia and the West /cLee Congdon. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2021] 4c©2017  a1 online resource (174 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aNIU Series in Slavic, East European, and Eurasian Studies00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tPREFACE -- tCHAPTER ONE. REVOLUTION AND WAR -- tCHAPTER TWO. IN THE GULAG -- tCHAPTER THREE. THORN IN THEIR SIDE -- tCHAPTER FOUR. IN THE WEST -- tCHAPTER FIVE. THE RETURN -- tCHAPTER SIX. WARNING TO THE WEST -- tNOTES -- tBIBLIOGRAPHY -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis study of Aleksandr Solzhenitsyn (1918–2008) and his writings focuses on his reflections on the religiopolitical trajectories of Russia and the West, understood as distinct civilizations. What perhaps most sets Russia apart from the West is the Orthodox Christian faith. The mature Solzhenitsyn returned to the Orthodox faith of his childhood while serving an eight-year sentence in the GULag Archipelago. He believed that when men forget God, communism or a similar catastrophe is likely to be their fate. In his examination of the author and his work, Lee Congdon explores the consequences of the atheistic socialism that drove the Russian revolutionary movement. Beginning with a description of the post-revolutionary Russia into which Solzhenitsyn was born, Congdon outlines the Bolshevik victory in the civil war, the origins of the concentration camp system, and the Bolsheviks' war on Christianity and the Russian Orthodox Church. He then focuses on Solzhenitsyn's arrest near the war's end, his time in the labor camps, and his struggle with cancer. Congdon describes his time in exile and increasing alienation from the Western way of life, as well as his return home and his final years. He concludes with a reminder of Solzhenitsyn's warning to the West—that it was on a path parallel to that which Russia had followed into the abyss. This important study will appeal to scholars and educated general readers with an interest in Solzhenitsyn, Russia, Christianity, and the fate of Western civilization.    aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aEast and West. 4aHistory. 4aPolitical Science & Political History. 4aSoviet & East European History. 7aHISTORY / Russia & the Former Soviet Union.2bisacsh  aKennan’s socio-cultural criticism, Critics of American foreign policy, Critics of American decline, Critics of nuclear armament.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311066587108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishz978311075400108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021z9783110753776oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2021 Englishz978311075408708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2021z9783110753851oZDB-23-DEG40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150175541540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501755415423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781501755415.jpg  a978-3-11-066587-1  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  a978-3-11-075400-1  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishb2021  a978